ine, Brittany, France":"Vitré-Est, Rennes, Ille-et-Vilaine, Brittany, France","Fourgeres, Rennes, Ille-et-Vilaine, Bretagne, France":"Rennes, Ille-et-Vilaine, Brittany, France","France":"France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"d'Aubrey","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (mainly Lincolnshire; of Norman origin): habitational name for someone from any of several places in northern France called Aubigny, named with the Gallo-Roman personal name <i>Albinius</i> (a derivative of Latin <i>albus</i> ‘white’; compare   Albin  ) + the habitational suffix <i>-acum</i>. Compare   Dabney  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Albin","meanings":["English, French, and German: from the personal name <i>Albin</i> (from Latin <i>Albinus</i>, a derivative of <i>albus</i> ‘white’). In England this is generally a variant of   Alban  . The usual spelling of the French name is   Aubin  . The personal name was especially popular in Austria, Lombardy, and Savoy, where it absorbed the ancient Germanic name <i>Albuin</i> (which is composed of the elements <i>alb</i> ‘elf’ + <i>win</i> ‘friend’; compare   Alvin  ). This was the name of the Lombard leader (died 572) who made himself king of northern Italy, and also of various Christian saints, including a bishop of Brixen (Bressanone) in South Tyrol.","Galician (<b>Albín</b>): habitational name from any of the four places called Albín in Galicia (Spain), from Latin <i>(villa) Albini</i>."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Génergaude d'Aubrey de la Vicaire was born in 0970, in Ille-et-Vilaine, Brittany, France. She married Riwallon de Vitré, Vicarius de Vitré, Lord of Vitré and Aubroy from 0975 to 1005, in Vitré-Est, Rennes, Ille-et-Vilaine, Brittany, France. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. She died about 1038, in her hometown, at the age of 69, and was buried in Saint-Georges, Ardennes, Champagne-Ardenne, France."},"et":{"970–about 1038":"0970–umbes 1038","0980–1040":"0980–1040","1003–105